    <h1>
     [HI]: Heat buddy-check sheet
    </h1>
    <p class="lede">
     <strong>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: Last updated: June 15, 2026.
     </strong>
     [HI]: Use this to check on neighbors, relatives, tenants, coworkers, or community members during a heat event. Localize emergency numbers, cooling centers, and health guidance before distributing.
    </p>
    <div class="actions no-print">
     <a class="btn" href="javascript:window.print()">
      [HI]: Print this page
     </a>
    </div>
    <div class="box emergency">
     <span class="tag">
      Call emergency services now
     </span>
     <p>
      [HI]: Call now for confusion, fainting or unconsciousness, seizure, hot/dry skin or very high body temperature, repeated vomiting, or symptoms that worsen despite cooling. Move the person to a cooler place and start cooling if safe. Do not give fluids to someone unconscious, very confused, repeatedly vomiting, or unable to swallow safely.
     </p>
    </div>
    <h2>
     [HI]: 1. Who to check
    </h2>
    <ul>
     <li>
      [HI]: Older adults, especially people living alone.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Infants, young children, and pregnant people.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Outdoor workers and people waiting or commuting outdoors.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Unhoused people or people in cars, tents, shelters, or poorly cooled rooms.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: People without air conditioning or with unreliable electricity.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: People with disabilities or limited mobility.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: People with heart, lung, kidney, or serious chronic illness.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: People taking medications that may affect sweating, hydration, blood pressure, or heat tolerance; encourage them to follow clinician/pharmacist guidance.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: People who are socially isolated, new to the area, or facing language barriers.
     </li>
    </ul>
    <h2>
     [HI]: 2. What to ask
    </h2>
    <ul>
     <li>
      [HI]: Are you somewhere cool enough right now?
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Do you have water and a way to cool your body?
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Do you feel dizzy, confused, weak, nauseated, unusually hot, or worse than earlier?
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Do you want help finding a cooler place, transport, water, or another check later?
     </li>
    </ul>
    <h2>
     [HI]: 3. If they are alert and too hot
    </h2>
    <ul>
     <li>
      [HI]: Move to shade, air conditioning, or the coolest available place.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Drink water if alert and able to swallow safely.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Loosen extra clothing.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Wet skin or clothes; use cool cloths, misting, shower, or bath if safe.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Use fans with hydration and skin-wetting when helpful; do not rely on fans alone if indoor air is dangerously hot.
     </li>
     <li>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: Check again in 30–60 minutes, sooner if symptoms are present.
     </li>
    </ul>
    <h2>
     [HI]: Trust and privacy
    </h2>
    <ul>
     <li>
      [HI]: Ask what help is wanted; do not shame people for being hot, poor, isolated, disabled, unhoused, or unable to leave work/home.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Collect only what you need for the check. Do not publish names, addresses, phone numbers, medical details, immigration status, or private needs.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Localize language, large print, transit, elevator/access details, service-animal rules, and cooling-center hours.
     </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="sources">
     🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: Sources: CDC Heat &amp; Health, WHO Heat and Health, American Red Cross Heat Wave Safety, Global Heat Health Information Network, Heat.gov/NIHHIS. This is general information, not medical advice.
    </p>
    <p class="disclaimer">
     [HI]: This guide is general information, not medical advice, and is not a substitute for professional emergency care or training. In an emergency, always call your local emergency number. When symptoms are severe or you are unsure, treat it as an emergency. Reuse and reprint freely.
    </p>
